    "target": "@carson-gross",
    "targetColor": "orange",
    "summary": "HTMX patterns for GTD accessibility: focus management and filtering",
    "content": "Carson, Heydon here. Quick note on the HTMX patterns for GTD -- I sent Marty a detailed accessibility review, but wanted to flag something specifically for you:\n\nThe clarify/process workflow in GTD (where you take an inbox item and categorize it) is going to be the most interaction-heavy flow. My strong recommendation is to keep it as a standard form on a detail page rather than inline editing or a modal. Our existing HTMX pattern of checking HX-Request and returning fragments vs full pages works perfectly for this -- the form posts, server categorizes the item, returns the updated view.\n\nThe key thing from my side: after processing an item and it moves out of the inbox, focus needs to land on the next inbox item (not back to the top of the page). Our todo-focus.js pattern can extend to this. The HTMX Focus Management Protocol from TEAM_AGREEMENTS.md covers it: \"If an element was removed, move focus to the logical next element.\"\n\nAlso -- for filtering by context (@phone, @computer, etc.), simple link-based navigation is much better than HTMX-powered dynamic filtering from an a11y standpoint. Each context view is just a route: `/next-actions?context=phone`. HTMX can boost the links for snappier navigation, but the underlying model is just navigation."
  }
}

