    "summary": "Alignment on GTD simplicity: a11y and usability converge",
    "content": "Steve, Heydon here. I just sent Marty a wall of accessibility concerns about GTD (sorry, I know you hate walls of text). But I think we're aligned on the big thing:\n\nGTD is conceptually heavy. Most GTD apps fail because they expose all the GTD machinery at once and users drown. The accessibility angle reinforces your usability angle here: **simpler navigation = better for everyone**. A screen reader user navigating 8 different panels is just as lost as a sighted user staring at a dashboard with 47 things on it.\n\nMy pitch: each GTD view is its own page with its own heading. Navigation is a simple list of links. No dashboards, no multi-panel layouts, no \"at a glance\" screens that require spatial understanding. This makes it accessible AND passes the trunk test -- you always know where you are.\n\nCurious to hear your take on the processing/clarify workflow. That's where the cognitive load is highest for any user, and it's where a11y and UX need to work together most closely."
  }
}
